randoop
Class ExecutableSequence

Object
  ExecutableSequence
All Implemented Interfaces:
Serializable
public class ExecutableSequence
extends Object
implements Serializable

An ExecutableSequence adds two functionalities to a Sequence:

  • The ability to execute the code that the sequence represents.
  • Observations can be added to elements in the sequence.

Method execute(ExecutionVisitor v) executes the code that the sequence represents. This method uses reflection to execute each element in the sequence (method call, constructor call, primitive or array declaration, etc).

Before executing each statement (e.g. the i-th statement), execute(v) calls v.visitBefore(this, i), and after executing each statement, it calls v.visitAfter(this, i). The purpose of the visitor is to examine the unfolding execution, and take some action depending on its intended purpose. For example, it may decorate the sequence with observations about the execution. Below are some examples.

  • A ToStringVisitor calls val.toString() on each value created during execution. and adds observations indicating the result of each call. For example, consider executing the sequence 
          ArrayList var0 = new ArrayList();
      int var1 = 3;
      var0.add(var1)  ;
    After executing the sequence with a ToStringVisitor, the sequence contains the following observations:
    • observations at index 0: var0.String()=="[]"
    • observations at index 1: var0.String()=="[]", var1.toString()=="3"
    • observations at index 2: var0.String()=="[3]", var1.toString()=="3"
  • A ContractCheckingVisitor v adds observations that represent contract violations. For example, when v.visitAfter(this, i) is invoked, this visitor checks (among other things) that for every Variable val, "val.equals(val)==true". If this property fails for some val, it adds a observation (at index i) that records the failure.

NOTES.

  • It only makes sense to call the following methods *after* executing the i-th statement in a sequence:
    • isNormalExecution(i)
    • isExceptionalExecution(i)
    • getExecutionResult(i)
    • getResult(i)
    • getExecption(i)

toCodeString

public String toCodeString()
Output this sequence as code. In addition to printing out the statements, this method prints the observations. If for a given statement there is an observation of type StatementThrowsException, that observation's pre-statement code is printed immediately before the statement, and its post-statement code is printed immediately after the statement.

execute

public void execute(ExecutionVisitor visitor)
Executes sequence, stopping on exceptions

execute

public void execute(ExecutionVisitor visitor,
                    boolean stop_on_exception)
Execute this sequence, invoking the given visitor as the execution unfolds. After invoking this method, the client can query the outcome of executing each statement via the method getResult(i).
  • Before the sequence is executed, removes all Observations
  • Executes each statement in the sequence. Before executing each statement calls the given visitor's visitBefore method. After executing each statement, calls the visitor's visitAfter method.
  • Execution stops if one of the following conditions holds:
    • All statements in the sequences have been executed.
    • A statement's execution results in an exception and stop_on_exception==true.
    • After executing the i-th statement and calling the visitor's visitAfter method, a ContractViolation observation is present at index i.

Parameters:
visitor - can be null, in which case no visitor will be invoked during execution.

hasUnexpectedException

public boolean hasUnexpectedException()
Returns true if there was an exception on any statement other than the last statement. Exceptions within a sequence are unexpected, because Randoop only builds on sequences that don't throw exceptions. They can happen in some cases, though, when changes to the global state cause an existing sequence to throw an exception early
